SIMPLE: louse
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Louse
<hw>Louse</hw> <pr>(lous)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Lice</plw> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧s)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>lous</ets>,
AS. <ets>l⟦umac⟧s</ets>, pl. <ets>l⟦ymac⟧s</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>luis</ets>, G. <ets>laus</ets>, OHG. <ets>l⟦umac⟧s</ets>, Icel.
<ets>l⟦umac⟧s</ets>, Sw. <ets>lus</ets>, Dan. <ets>luus</ets>; perh. so
named because it is destructive, and akin to E. <ets>lose</ets>,
<ets>loose</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Any one of
numerous species of small, wingless, suctorial, parasitic insects
belonging to a tribe (<fam>Pediculina</fam>), now usually regarded as
degraded Hemiptera. To this group belong of the lice of man and other
mammals; <as>as, the head <ex>louse</ex> of man (<spn>Pediculus
capitis</spn>), the body <ex>louse</ex> (<spn>Pediculus
vestimenti</spn>), and the crab <ex>louse</ex> (<spn>Phthirius
pubis</spn>), and many others</as>. See <cref>Crab louse</cref>,
<cref>Dog louse</cref>, <cref>Cattle louse</cref>, etc., under
<er>Crab</er>, <er>Dog</er>, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any one of numerous small mandibulate insects,
mostly parasitic on birds, and feeding on the feathers. They are known
as Mallophaga, or bird lice, though some occur on the hair of mammals.
They are usually regarded as degraded Pseudoneuroptera. See
<er>Mallophaga</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any one of the numerous species of aphids, or plant
lice. See <er>Aphid</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Any small crustacean parasitic on fishes. See
<er>Branchiura</er>, and <er>Ichthvophthira</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The term is also applied to various other parasites; as,
the whale <xex>louse</xex>, bee<xex>louse</xex>, horse
<xex>louse</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Louse fly</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a parasitic
dipterous insect of the group Pupipara. Some of them are wingless, as
the bee louse.</cd> -- <col><b>Louse mite</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>,
<cd>any one of numerous species of mites which infest mammals and birds,
clinging to the hair and feathers like lice. They belong to
<gen>Myobia</gen>, <gen>Dermaleichus</gen>, <gen>Mycoptes</gen>, and
several other genera.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Louse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Louse
<hw>Louse</hw> <pr>(louz)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To clean from
lice.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧You sat and <xex>loused</xex> him.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lousewort</ent>⟦br⟧
